1
00:00:01,040 --> 00:00:10,040
So my project is called the quad-CAN filter tester. Its job is to test this quad-CAN filter.

2
00:00:10,040 --> 00:00:17,040
This quad-CAN filter incorporates five connections, CAN1, CAN2, LIN, CAN3 and CAN4.

3
00:00:17,040 --> 00:00:22,040
All of these connections are being tested by this quad-CAN filter tester,

4
00:00:22,040 --> 00:00:29,040
and the results are being showed onto this PC when it's plugged in into the USB.

5
00:00:29,040 --> 00:00:34,040
Which means all the results can be shown on the terminal, which is very nice.

6
00:00:34,040 --> 00:00:46,060
Once I will turn on the quad-CAN filter tester, the LEDs flash onto this quad-CAN filter,

7
00:00:46,060 --> 00:00:52,060
meaning that the two LEDs flash here, meaning that all the CAN connections are good.

8
00:00:52,060 --> 00:01:01,060
And if I go to the terminal here, the C connections, as you can see, which is CAN1, CAN2 and LIN,

9
00:01:01,060 --> 00:01:08,060
all of them are okay, and the C1 connections, CAN3, CAN4, is also okay.

10
00:01:08,060 --> 00:01:13,060
These are the C, and these are the C1 connections.

11
00:01:13,060 --> 00:01:19,060
So C connections are here, C1 connections are here, and the same goes for this.

12
00:01:19,060 --> 00:01:27,060
Now, in order to fully test all of the capabilities of this project,

13
00:01:27,060 --> 00:01:33,060
I can firstly turn off the quad-CAN filter and let's just say something happens.

14
00:01:33,060 --> 00:01:40,060
Actually, the tested component is not working, and let's just remove one of these parts here,

15
00:01:40,060 --> 00:01:42,060
which is the C connections.

16
00:01:42,060 --> 00:01:49,060
This C little filter is removed, which means what I'm going to see on the terminal here

17
00:01:49,060 --> 00:01:56,060
is that all of the C connections, the thing that I've removed now, are going to be labeled as error.

18
00:01:56,060 --> 00:02:01,060
So I turn on the quad-CAN filter tester.

19
00:02:01,060 --> 00:02:04,060
The same thing happens.

20
00:02:05,060 --> 00:02:11,060
The only thing here is that the C connections are labeled as error,

21
00:02:11,060 --> 00:02:15,060
which is what I've anticipated, meaning everything is fine.

22
00:02:15,060 --> 00:02:18,060
Same thing I can do with this.

23
00:02:18,060 --> 00:02:22,060
I can remove the C1 connections here,

24
00:02:22,060 --> 00:02:27,060
meaning that it's basically empty and nothing is going to really work here.

25
00:02:27,060 --> 00:02:35,060
And as I'll turn off and I'll turn on the quad-CAN filter tester,

26
00:02:35,060 --> 00:02:41,060
all of them are going to be shown as error, so C and C1 connections.

27
00:02:41,060 --> 00:02:48,060
Now, what I can do now is I can just put all of these connections on.

28
00:02:48,060 --> 00:02:55,060
So I put in the C connections here, and I will also put in the C1 connections.

29
00:02:55,060 --> 00:03:01,060
It's very hard to do this with one hand, but here you go.

30
00:03:01,060 --> 00:03:10,060
All of them are being put in, and now my job is to turn off the quad-CAN filter

31
00:03:10,060 --> 00:03:13,060
and then turn it on again.

32
00:03:13,060 --> 00:03:17,060
Mind you, all of the C and C1 connections here are plugged in,

33
00:03:17,060 --> 00:03:25,060
which means that all of the connections should show an okay time for each of those connections.

34
00:03:25,060 --> 00:03:34,720
It shows that the test is successful, and once the test is failed,

35
00:03:34,720 --> 00:03:37,720
it's going to say test is failed.

36
00:03:37,720 --> 00:03:39,720
And that's pretty much it.

37
00:03:39,720 --> 00:03:45,720
That is my whole quad-CAN filter tester software project.

38
00:03:45,720 --> 00:03:52,720
So hopefully you've enjoyed this, and take care.
